headline: Boeing Stock Sale Was Supposed to Mark the Bottom. How Low Shares Could Go.
summary: Boeing  is starting to show progress in its turnaround plans.  Shares of the plane maker closed at $139.10 on Wednesday, the first time shares have closed below $140 since October 2022 and below the $143 level that Boeing recently sold stock.  New CEO Kelly Ortberg has a list of things he wants to accomplish to turn around the struggling company.

headline: Boeing hires Northrop executive to take over Pentagon projects
summary: Miller's hiring as general manager of Phantom Works at Boeing Defense, Space and Security (BDS) had been in the works before the arrival of new Boeing CEO Kelly Ortberg.  Boeing's defense business has been struggling under the weight of budget-busting older contracts, but Ortberg said in October that the unit which makes helicopters, fighter jets and missiles remains "core" to the company's future.

headline: Boeing Hires Northrop Executive to Revamp Pentagon Projects
summary: Boeing  has poached an executive from defense rival  Northrop Grumman  to run its Phantom Works division, which oversees research efforts for its Pentagon business and is involved in bidding for U.S. government projects.  Colin Miler, a former Air Force commander who oversaw aeronautics engineering at Northrop, will take over the division, the jet maker told employees on Thursday.  The Phantom Works division is also being combined into a single division.

headline: US weekly jobless claims fall; unemployment rolls shrink
summary: The number of Americans filing new applications for unemployment benefits fell last week, suggesting the labor market continued to chug along and that the abrupt slowdown in job growth in October was an aberration.  Initial claims for state unemployment benefits dropped 4,000 to a seasonally adjusted 217,000 for the week ended Nov. 9, the Labor Department said on Thursday.  Claims surged in early October amid distortions from  Hurricanes Helene and Milton as a well as a strike by factory workers at Boeing, but layoffs have remained historically low, which is underpinning the economy.
